<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1928-05-02T17:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1928-05-02T17:00:00-05:00" n="310" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d310">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">493.11 N 15/136: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">MacMurray</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1928-05-02T18:00:00-04:00"><hi rend="italic">May 2, 1928—6
                                        p.m.</hi></date></dateline></opener>
                        <p>141. Your 290, April 30, 4 p.m. Secretaries of Presbyterian Board decline
                            to act before Board meeting May 14. Department believes Board might then
                            be persuaded to assent but recommends that under the circumstances you
                            endeavor to find and appoint some one else. Department suggests for your
                            consideration Frank S. Williams, Registrar of China Trade Act,<note n="23" xml:id="d310fn23">Act approved Sept. 19, 1922 (42 Stat.
                                849).</note> but leaves choice to you.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Kellogg</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>